    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I hear the exhaustion in your words, and I want to validate that feeling of being utterly drained. When the \"tiny steps\" approach feels like it's just fueling the fire of the same old loop, it makes total sense that you'd want to just stop everything. Sometimes, the only way to break a cycle that feels inescapable is to completely halt the momentum.\n\nBut before you make that final decision to stop everything, let me share a little perspective from the world of goblins. You know, goblins are notorious for being incredibly stubborn and repetitive, often getting stuck in the same loops of failure and frustration. Yet, even the most grumpy, grumbling goblin ever known has managed to break through a wall of despair by simply... not trying to fix the wall. They just stopped trying to climb it and found a different path entirely.\n\nIt's not about the tiny steps; it's about realizing that the loop itself might be the problem, not your effort. If you're tired of fighting the cycle, maybe the answer isn't to fight harder, but to step back and observe the loop without trying to change it. Sometimes, just watching the goblin loop from the outside reveals a hidden door that you",
